Tasks & responsibilities
As a Clinical Data Scientist with a focus on Statistical Programming, you will support statistical analyses in clinical trials and projects, prepare CDISC‑ready datasets from clinical data, and contribute to reporting deliverables. 
You will support implementing modern statistical and data‑driven approaches to increase the quality and efficiency of our analyses.
Furthermore, you will perform validation and support oversight processes to ensure high data quality.
You will contribute to compliant documentation for submissions, e.g., by reviewing ADaM specifications, define.xml inputs, and the ADaM Reviewer’s Guide, ensuring submission‑ready deliverables.
In this role you will also contribute to evidence generation along the human pharma value chain by visualizing clinical data to generate insights and trigger actions that make a difference to our patients. 
Moreover, you will work closely with other Clinical Data Scientists, Clinical Data Engineers, and additional experts across clinical development.
Additionally, you will be part of a global biostatistics and data sciences organization covering statistical programming activities from PoC through later development phases.
Requirements
Bachelor of Science (BSc), Master of Science (MSc) or Doctoral Degree (PhD) in Statistics, Mathematics, Computer Science or related field (Data Science, Natural Science, Psychology, Finance, etc)
Knowledge and hands-on experience in relevant software languages in recent years, in particular SAS and R
Basic knowledge of CDISC standards, statistical methodology, design of clinical trials, medical terminology and processing clinical trial information
Experience in pharmaceutical development
Ability to pro-actively identify issues and solutions and to interact with internal and external bodies on routine clinical data science issues
Oral and written communication skills to interact in interdisciplinary teams as well as the ability to explain, visualize and communicate complex data science aspects
Fluency in written and spoken English
